Statistics show that Gauteng, which experts predict to have the highest number of cases by the end of the year, and the Eastern Cape are still lagging about three weeks behind the Western Cape but could catch up by early July during mid-winter. On May 8, there were 4 497 confirmed Covid-19 cases in the Western Cape and 88 deaths and by Monday it had escalated to 22 567 cases and 525 deaths. Gauteng and the Eastern Cape both only reached the 4 000 case mark on Monday.  * For the latest on the Covid-19 outbreak, visit IOL's special #Coronavirus page. ** If you think you have been exposed to the Covid-19 virus, please call the 24-hour hotline on 0800 029 999 or visitÂ sacoronavirus.co.za  